Solid Print, Prudent FY26 Guide, But Macro Uncertainty Remains An OverhangBILL delivered a solid F4Q as revenue of \(\) 383.3m\((+11.5\%)\) came in ahead of expectations of \(\) 376.3m\((+9.5\%)\) . Transaction revs grew \(17.7\%\) y/y, TPV was up \(13.4\%\) at \(\) 86.1\(bn, with 32.9mn transactions processed (+17.5\% y/y). The initial FY26 guide assumes 10\% y/y rev growth and core rev growth of +13.5\% y/y at the midpoint. We would note that float revenue will pressure total revenue growth by 160bps in FY26. Mgmt's macro commentary was consistent with last quarter, noting ongoing pressure on SMBs, continued supplier sensitivity to acceptance costs, and some Q4 spending pulled forward ahead of tariff headlines. This backdrop underpins the outlook for flat TPV per customer. BILL recently signed a strategic embed partnership with a F500 software company to expand BILL's distribution. It was also encouraging to hear mid- market momentum is building, with customer growth outpacing the average by \(\sim 5\) pts in FY25 and mid- market customers delivering \(\sim 2x\) TPV and \(\sim 2x\) users vs. SMB, which supports the upmarket mix thesis. Monetization came in ahead of plan on broader adoption of higher take- rate ad valorem products, with ad valorem penetration ex- FI up to \(14.3\%\) from \(13.8\%\) , but the debate remains whether take- rate gains can outpace macro and payment- mix headwind. With ACH and checks still \(\sim 85\%\) of annual payment volume, customers appear to be sticking with lower value rails, which keeps pressure on mgmt to lift the overall take rate. Mgmt announced a new share buyback plan of up to \(\) 300m\(in FY26, likely providing N/T support for the shares though catalysts that unlock any N/T upside remains unclear. The call featured Rohini Jain, the new CFO, who provided a more transparent outlook and emphasized a disciplined approach to profitability as BILL continues to scale. Bottom line: While the long- term opportunity for BILL to own the financial back- office suite for SMBs driven by payments, product expansion, and international growth, we believe macro uncertainty is likely to keep shares range- bound for now. Reiterate In Line and adj PT to \(\) 48\$

Recapping the quarter: Core rev (sub \(^+\) transaction) of \(\) 345.9m\(was up 14.8\% y/y exceeding consensus estimates of 12.9\%. Gross margins contracted 77bps y/y to 84.2\%, vs. consensus of 83.8\%. Operating margin also slipped 277bps y/y to 14.7\%, vs. consensus at 12.2\%. EPS of\) \ \(0.60\) came in above our and Street expectations of \(\) 0.41\(. OCF of\) \ \(83.8\) mn came in above consensus estimates of \(\) 80.4\(mn, and FCF came in at\) \ \(68.5m n\) vs. consensus of \(\) 61.7m n\$

Using a revenue multiple, our \(\) 48PT\(implies shares remain range bound at 3.0x EV/CY26 sales.\)

Economic conditions worsen, causing a pause in IT spending and creating a tougher SMB market, churn ticks higher, intensifying competitive concerns from larger vendors moving down market, and hyper- growth moderates and the valuation re- rates.

Evercore ISI's recommendations are based on a stock's total forecasted return over the next 12 months. Total forecasted return is equal to the expected percentage price return plus gross dividend yield. We divide our stocks under coverage into three primary ratings categories, with the following return guidelines:
Outperform- the total forecasted return is expected to be greater than the expected total return of the analyst's coverage sector.
In Line- the total forecasted return is expected to be in line with the expected total return of the analyst's coverage sector.
Underperform- the total forecasted return is expected to be less than the expected total return of the analyst's coverage sector.

Coverage Suspended- the rating and target price have been removed pursuant to Evercore ISI policy when Evercore is acting in an advisory capacity in a merger or strategic transaction involving this company and in certain other circumstances.

Rating Suspended- Evercore ISI has suspended the rating and target price for this stock because there is not sufficient fundamental basis for determining, or there are legal, regulatory or policy constraints around publishing, a rating or target price. The previous rating and target price, if any, are no longer in effect for this company and should not be relied upon.
Prior to October 10, 2015, the "Coverage Suspended" and "Rating Suspended" categories were included in the category "Suspended."

FINRA requires that members who use a ratings system with terms other than "Buy," "Hold/Neutral" and "Sell" to equate their own ratings to these categories.
